author: fifthjack_TTV
body:
Posted this yesterday and I got downvoted… guess I was kinda right. Tlry going to $24 today

Yo so this is my analysis of TLRY and why I think it’s bullish: 

 1 year+ chart:
Just apply the Fibonacci curve. We are way below 38% and got lots to run. We should easily be able to hit $25 and have a run for $30+ (IMO either end of this week or beginning of the next week unless fed tapering screws us or GME ER takes the whole sector down)

1-3 month chart: looks extremely bullish. Key resistances at $20.50 -$21.00 and $30. Strong support at $14, $17 -$18. Overall, bulls are in charge. Growing 4% a day steadily past 2 weeks with maybe 1 Rex day. 

1 week chart: we’ve been able to hold the $18 support and forming a new one around $19.90-20.10 range. We are slowly breaking down the $21 wall that was created back in Jan-Feb. in past 3 days we have hit $20.50-$21.00 range over 4 times and bounced back. But you can tel that it’s looking bullish because while we are bouncing back at the same ceiling price, the support price is steadily increasing. This creates an ascending triangle and is a sign of a strong bull coming up

author: NohoTwoPointOh
body:
Re: Cylance, I (also?) worked in that industry for many years and know their folks and folks that compete against them.  Cylance is NOT the first company to do that.  Not by far.  

Pre-Dell SecureWorks, Damballa, and a little In-Q-Tel-funded shop in Northern Virginia were all applying machine-learning and AI to cybersecurity.  Roughly so by today's standards (especially in SecureWorks' case), but they were all doing it quite early. Damballa came out of Georgia Tech's ATDC incubator.  They had an interesting Chinese fellow that did machine-learning analysis of covert C&C channels. 

I had a red Passport.  That thing had I-beams in the side of it.  Tough as nails and fast as hell.  Miss that phone terribly.  Had to ditch it when they started neutering mainstream apps (as I could run YouTube and multitask without the pro subscription).  My last phone was a KeyOne before I went Samsung.  Ick.

author: Anonplox
body:
Currently the interest rate of buying a house in Canada is below 1%. If the interest rates from the Bank of Canada increase even to 1-2%, people’s mortgage payments are going to skyrocket, because they bought a house during a pandemic when rates were predatory to save the economy.

Now that things are getting back to normal, and Canada is leading the charge of vaccines, I see the bank of Canada raising interest rates sooner than later.

In fact there’s an article here that talks about rates in the US, at least, increased by 2023. That’s not far off. And as we know, Canada follows US moves closely. [Federal Reserve Officials Project Rate Increases in 2023](https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/16/business/economy/fed-meeting-inflation.html?campaign_id=60&emc=edit_na_20210616&instance_id=0&nl=breaking-news&ref=headline&regi_id=76475603&segment_id=60864&user_id=1d5018a087ae3465a62b080157ab67a9)

The market is hot, and realtors know this. They are making crazy amounts of commission, along with their partnered brokers.  Most of these people just want to put a deal through before everything goes to shit.

In my area, there are empty houses. Lawns over grown, and no movement around the properties for months. 

It’s a shit show waiting to happen, and I anticipate it to be bigger than the 2008 market crash.

In fact, Hamilton, Ontario is considered to be more expensive to live than LA. Fucking LA.  Let me tel you, Hamilton is NO LA. https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/hamilton/affordability-canada-1.6034606
